SIMPLE: roast
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Roast
<hw>Roast</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Roasted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Roasting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>rosten</ets>, OF.
<ets>rostir</ets>, F. <ets>r⟦ocir⟧tir</ets>; of German origin; cf. OHG.
<ets>r⟦omac⟧sten</ets>, G. <ets>r⟦oum⟧sten</ets>, fr. OHG.
<ets>r⟦omac⟧st</ets>, <ets>r⟦omac⟧sta</ets>, gridiron, G.
<ets>rost</ets>; cf. AS. <ets>hyrstan</ets> to roast.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To cook by exposure to radiant heat before a fire; <as>as, to
<ex>roast</ex> meat on a spit, or in an oven open toward the fire and
having reflecting surfaces within</as>; also, to cook in a close
oven.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cook by surrounding with hot embers, ashes, sand,
etc.; <as>as, to <ex>roast</ex> a potato in ashes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In eggs boiled and <qex>roasted</qex> there is scarce difference
to be discerned.</q> <rj><qau>BAcon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To dry and parch by exposure to heat; <as>as, to
<ex>roast</ex> coffee; to <ex>roast</ex> chestnuts, or
peanuts.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Hence, to heat to excess; to heat violently; to
burn.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Roasted</xex> in wrath and fire.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Metal.)</fld> <def>To dissipate by heat the
volatile parts of, as ores.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To banter severely.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>
<rj><au>Atterbury.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Roast
<hw>Roast</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cook meat, fish,
etc., by heat, as before the fire or in an oven.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He could <qex>roast</qex>, and seethe, and broil, and fry.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To undergo the process of being roasted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Roast
<hw>Roast</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which is roasted; a piece of
meat which has been roasted, or is suitable for being roasted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A fat swan loved he best of any <qex>roost</qex> [roast].</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To rule the roast</b></col>, <cd>to be at the head of
affairs.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧The new-made duke that <xex>rules the
roast</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧</cs><-- = to rule the roost! -->
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Roast
<hw>Roast</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[For <ets>roasted</ets>.]</ety>
<def>Roasted; <as>as, <ex>roast</ex> beef</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roaster</ent>⟦br⟧
